  date        = {2020-09},
  doi         = {10.3386/w27872},
  abstract    = {We study a real small open economy with two key ingredients:
                 (i) partial segmentation of home and foreign bond markets and
                 (ii) a pecuniary externality that makes the real exchange rate
                 excessively volatile in response to capital flows. Partial
                 segmentation implies that, by intervening in the bond markets,
                 the central bank can affect the exchange rate and the spread
                 between home- and foreign-bond yields. Such interventions allow
                 the central bank to address the pecuniary externality, but they
                 are also costly, as foreigners make carry-trade profits. We
                 analytically characterize the optimal intervention policy that
                 solves this trade-off: (a) the optimal policy leans against the
                 wind, stabilizing the exchange rate; (b) it involves smooth
