                 bounds do not bind forever, the long run tax is indeed zero;
                 however, when preferences are recursive but non-additive across
                 time, the zero-capital-tax limit comes accompanied by zero
                 private wealth (zero tax base) or by zero labor taxes (first
                 best). Finally, we explain why the equivalence of a positive
                 capital tax with ever rising consumption taxes does not provide
                 a firm rationale against capital taxation.},
  series      = {Working Paper Series}
}

